The '''1977 Kentucky Wildcats football team''' represented the [[University of Kentucky]] in the [[1977 college football season]]. The Wildcats scored 252 points while allowing 111 points. The Wildcats won a share of the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] championship with [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] and finished the season ranked #6 in the final [[AP Poll]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Final 1977 AP Poll at AP Poll Archive.com|url=http://www.appollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?seasonid=1977&appollid=479|work=|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5hF6yISlJ|archivedate=2009-06-02|deadurl=no|accessdate=2009-05-31}}</ref>
==Regular season== *In the Border Battle, Kentucky beat [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] by a score of 21-17. Entering that game, Kentucky had seven injured starters unable to play, including quarterback [[Derrick Ramsey]], whose arm was injured so badly he could not throw the football.<ref>[http://www.kentucky.com/2011/09/04/1869157/mark-story-uk-footballs-greatest.html#storylink=mirelated Story, Mark, UK football's greatest wins at Commonwealth, Lexington Herald-Leader, September 4, 2011]</ref> Tennessee jumped out to a 17-14 lead when backup quarterback Mike Deaton completed a 36 yard pass to Felix Wilson; teh injured Ramsey then entered the game and led Kentucky to a touchdown.<ref>[http://www.kentucky.com/2011/09/04/1869157/mark-story-uk-footballs-greatest.html#storylink=mirelated Story, Mark, UK football's greatest wins at Commonwealth, Lexington Herald-Leader, September 4, 2011]</ref> Tennessee's offense then took the ball to Kentucky's 22 yard line but Tennessee quarterback [[Jimmy Streater]] fumbled due to a hit by Kentucky All-American defensive end [[Art Still]], and linebacker [[Kelly Kirchbaum]] recovered the ball to preserve the win.<ref>[http://www.kentucky.com/2011/09/04/1869157/mark-story-uk-footballs-greatest.html#storylink=mirelated Story, Mark, UK football's greatest wins at Commonwealth, Lexington Herald-Leader, September 4, 2011]</ref>
